name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: Dems can keep winning cities comfortably and can fumble in and out of a narrow house majority with the current suburbs-are-rural view. Or they can adopt a suburbs-are-urban view and embrace a popular majority that is sitting there waiting to be the mandate for big changes (14/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: Tbc this isn’t “anti-rural”. It’s an agenda designed to appeal to where most people + voters live/work. Reframing political tendencies expressly as between rural + urban interests (with working class organized in both) will lead to compromises that help both. (13/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: Running on investing in urbanism - for better jobs, cheaper housing, good public schools, reliable transit, competent public health + safety, greater sustainability - is a winning appeal to voters in cities *and in suburbs* (12/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: The emotional + economic links btw suburbs + cities are already there and they’re deep. An agenda that speaks to both in a singular, shared vision is just not that hard of a sell if we commit to it (11/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: I can go through usual stats of GDP, job/pop growth, carbon emissions etc to make case but I can also point out basic feeling that most people in suburbs have - that they’re from “greater Hartford” or “outside Detroit” or “the burbs near Atlanta”. We feel it already (10/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: The key for Dems is identifying + messaging suburban areas *with urban cores* instead of falling for GOP trap and seeing them as rural-ish areas. They aren’t! Their fortunes are married to cities always have been - so run on making that link clearer + better for everyone (9/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: But the Dem strategy this cycle missed permanently severing the GOP advantage in suburbs because it didn’t offer a new vision.  Anti-Trump was OK for now to beat him but it’s clearly not enough of a promise to govern and make our lives better (8/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: There are cracks in this message because of Trump. He tried doubling down on defending ‘white suburbia’ but it doesn’t quite match his cartoon understanding of them. So we’re starting at a good place! (7/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: This image of cities does a few useful things politically it 1) erases the working class/BIPOC/immigrant majority of voters in cities  2) erases the growing diversity of suburbs 3) delegitimizes any expressly pro-urban policy. Investing in cities is DOA in the Congress.  (6/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: Start by beating the GOP’s cynical game with cities of messaging them as somehow both “run by coastal elites” + violent hellholes run by minorities. The contradiction is laughable but they have their cake and eat it too cuz Dem leadership is afraid of being IDed as “urban”(5/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: Pretending we can compete against this (or that the US can sustain itself under it) and don’t need to commit today to major structural reforms is insanity or defeatism or both. There’s no other solution so let’s get started organizing for big changes. Ppl will come (4/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: The GOP rn obviously has a lot of structural help from the Constitution which favors rural states in the EC/senate, doesn’t recognize cities and often arbitrary divides their natural boundaries across state lines making it even harder to coordinate and govern. (3/14)

name: Pete 🔥#CancelRent🔥 Harrison
tweet: You can critique down ballot Dem strategy of bloodless appeals to suburbs (and it was flawed in messaging + voter outreach) but we have to win by 6-7 points to overcome the structural bias against cities and it’s really hard to do that (2/14)

name: Austin Smith
tweet: We’ve had a big victory in the last week obviously, but there is so much work to be done to decriminalize poverty. And this pandemic has made that abundantly clear. Divesting from systems of oppression is hard, necessary work. And capitalism is one of those systems.

name: Austin Smith
tweet: I’m no saint but the encounter reminded me yet again that this country fails to provide for its citizens, many of whom work themselves to the bone while living in poverty. And that “free market capitalism” only works for an indescribably small group of people.

name: Austin Smith
tweet: He didn’t see his mere existence as worthy of the resources needed to live—another delusion of capitalism. And as a black man he’s part of a group that is historically more harmed by capitalism than others. (Ain’t no “capitalism” without slavery).

name: Austin Smith
tweet: We tie our worth to productivity and output in a way that is unsustainable. This man felt he needed to “earn his keep” in return for the money, a notion born out of the way the rich exploit the poor and working class.

name: Austin Smith
tweet: He then asked if I needed help with anything or could he carry my boxes from UPS. Obviously I said no. But the fact that this man, so clearly failed by the system, felt an obligation to earn this little bit of money I gave him speaks to how deeply indoctrinated we are.

name: Austin Smith
tweet: Capitalism is such a disease. While waiting in line outside a UPS store today, there was a homeless guy asking for money. I almost forgot that I’d gone to the ATM yesterday and had cash. I gave him some money.
